    lastVerifiedAt: "2026-05-09",
    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "When your last parent dies, you become an adult orphan. The phrase sounds odd because the word orphan is usually reserved for children. But geriatric social workers and bereavement researchers use it intentionally. The death of the second parent ends a primary identity that has shaped your life since birth: being someone's child. If you are 74, you have been someone's daughter or son for 74 years. The day after the funeral, that role is over. The shift is more disorienting than most people expect.\n\nThe grief itself is different from earlier life losses. After years of caregiving, the death is often a relief in some sense — the suffering ended, the bedside vigil ended, the daily emergencies ended. That relief is followed by guilt for feeling it, then by waves of sadness that come without warning. There is also the absence of the role. The caregiver who spent 30 to 50 hours per week on the parent's care now has an empty calendar. The phone stops ringing. The pharmacy stops calling. The hospice nurse stops coming. The house, if you cared for her in your home, is quiet in a new way.\n\nThe research on bereavement in late life shows several patterns. Most caregivers experience a period of intense grief lasting 6 to 12 months, with the first three months being the hardest. Anticipatory grief — the sadness that builds up during the long decline before death — often makes the post-death grief shorter than for people who lost a parent suddenly. But the identity reset takes longer, sometimes 18 to 24 months, because there is no map for who you are after caregiving ends. Bereavement support groups, individual therapy, and unhurried time with other people who have lived through the same thing all help. The Medicare Hospice Benefit covers up to 13 months of free bereavement counseling for the family after the death; that benefit goes unused in most cases because no one tells the family it exists.\n\nThere is also the practical side. Closing out a parent's life takes about a year of work: probate, taxes, canceling subscriptions and Social Security, sorting belongings, selling or renting the house, dealing with siblings on the estate. Most of this falls on the caregiver child. It can feel like a continuation of the caregiving job. The estate administration is not the same as grief work, but it overlaps. Many caregivers find themselves so busy with paperwork in the first six months that they do not begin to grieve until month seven, which is when family and friends have stopped checking in.\n\nFor caregivers over 65, there are two specific dimensions to plan for. First, your own mortality. The loss of your parent often makes you confront your own death in a new way. There is no buffer generation above you anymore. Second, the practical and financial future. You may have spent years and savings on your parent's care, and now you need to think about your own future care. This is an appropriate moment to update your own estate planning, set up an advance directive of your own if you have not, and talk with your adult children if you have them.\n\nThe steps below are not a checklist to rush through. They are a sequence to follow over the first 12 months. Take them slowly. Take some of them never. Grief and identity rebuilding have no timeline.\n\n(Sources: Center for the Study of Aging and Human Development at Duke University; National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization Bereavement Programs; American Psychological Association Grief Resources; Modern Loss at modernloss.com)",
